 efforts of any government that seeks to improve its responses to maritime violence. The bottom line is that maritime violence can be managed effectively enough to protect citizens and national economies that depend on the sea. Comprehensive in scope, the volume coheres around the premise that good governance in the maritime domain, though difficult, is worth the considerable resources required.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aMaritime terrorismxPrevention. 0aPiracyxPrevention. 0aSea-powerxInternational cooperation. 0aSea-power. 0aSecurity, International. 4aIncident Command. 4aIntegrated Strategy. 4aMaritime Governance. 4aMaritime Legal Framework. 4aMaritime Terrorism. 4aMaritime Violence. 4aMaritime. 4aPiracy. 4aPort Security. 4aSecurity Institutions. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh1 aShemella, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479863140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804798631423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804798631.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles